```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <omp.h>

/* Main computational kernel. The whole function will be timed,
   including the call and return. */
void kernel_jacobi_1d(int tsteps, int n,
                      std::vector<double>& A,
                      std::vector<double>& B) {
    // Value used in the stencil
    const double inv3 = 1.0 / 3.0;

    // Obtain raw pointers for faster indexed access
    double *a = A.data();
    double *b = B.data();

    // The outer time‑step loop must remain sequential because
    // each stage depends on the previous one.
    for (int t = 0; t < tsteps; ++t) {
        // First update B from A
        #pragma omp parallel for if(n > 1000) schedule(static, 256)
        for (int i = 1; i < n - 1; ++i) {
            b[i] = inv3 * (a[i - 1] + a[i] + a[i + 1]);
        }

        // Then update A from B
        #pragma omp parallel for if(n > 1000) schedule(static, 256)
        for (int i = 1; i < n - 1; ++i) {
            a[i] = inv3 * (b[i - 1] + b[i] + b[i + 1]);
        }
    }
}
```
This version keeps the original semantics while:

* Using raw pointers to avoid bounds checks in every iteration.
* Parallelizing the inner loops with OpenMP.
* Explicitly computing the stencil coefficient once (`inv3`).
* Applying a static schedule with a block size that is usually well matched
  to cache lines on modern x86‑64 CPUs.

